    <section class="faq-sec">
      <h2>Do Gummy Vitamins Work? — Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Do gummy vitamins actually work?</summary><p>Yes, for most nutrients. A 2023 study in <em>Nutrients</em> found gummy vitamins achieved 91-98% bioavailability compared to traditional tablets for most water-soluble vitamins. The gummy delivery format does not impair absorption when the product is properly formulated with clinically relevant doses and manufactured under quality-controlled conditions.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Are gummy vitamins as good as regular vitamins?</summary><p>For most nutrients, gummy vitamins are clinically equivalent to tablets and capsules. Studies on vitamin D3, B12, melatonin, biotin, and elderberry show no statistically significant difference in blood serum levels between gummy and pill delivery. Gummies consistently outperform pills in compliance — users are 37% more likely to take them daily.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>What are the downsides of gummy vitamins?</summary><p>The main disadvantages are sugar content (2-4g per serving), lower nutrient density for high-dose nutrients, shorter shelf life due to moisture-induced degradation, higher cost (2-5x more per serving than pills), and limited delivery of certain nutrients like iron, calcium, and high-dose omega-3. Sugar-free versions address the sugar concern.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Do gummy vitamins absorb properly?</summary><p>Yes. Chewing initiates digestion and mixes ingredients with salivary enzymes. For nutrients with sublingual absorption potential — melatonin and B12 — gummies may absorb slightly faster than swallowed pills. A 2015 <em>Clinical Therapeutics</em> study confirmed equivalent vitamin D3 absorption between gummy and tablet forms.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>How much sugar is in gummy vitamins?</summary><p>Most gummy vitamins contain 2-4 grams of sugar per serving (typically 2 gummies), equaling 8-16 calories. For context, a medium apple contains 19 grams of sugar. Sugar-free gummy vitamins using stevia, monk fruit, or allulose are now widely available and taste nearly identical to sugared versions.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Why did 80% of gummy vitamins fail testing?</summary><p>The widely cited 2017 ConsumerLab.com analysis found that 80% of tested gummy supplements failed quality standards, primarily for containing less active ingredient than labeled. This was a manufacturing maturity problem, not a format problem. Failure rates dropped to under 25% by 2024. Products with USP or NSF certification now reliably meet label claims.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Are gummy vitamins bad for your teeth?</summary><p>Gummy vitamins can stick to teeth and contain sugar, but the amount (2-4g) and brief exposure time make dental impact minimal for adults who brush regularly. Choose sugar-free gummies, rinse with water after chewing, and take gummies before brushing rather than after to further reduce any risk.</p></details>
      <details class="fq"><summary>Which vitamins should you NOT take as gummies?</summary><p>Certain nutrients are better as pills: iron (metallic taste, gelling agent interactions), calcium (dose too large for gummy form), high-dose omega-3 (would require 8-40 gummies daily), and probiotics (live bacteria have poor viability in moist gummy matrix). For these nutrients, capsules or tablets are more effective.</p></details>
    </section>

